    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_155772049" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/155772049" />
    <a title="jv poore" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5157918-jv-poore"><img alt="jv poore" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1570108420p2/5157918.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/155772049?book_show_action=true">Mar 21, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="jv poore" class="user" itemprop="url" name="jv poore" href="/user/show/5157918-jv-poore">jv poore</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5157918-jv-poore?shelf=young-adult">young-adult</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5157918-jv-poore?shelf=re-read">re-read</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer155772049" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer627315700022133384">Re-Read this over the weekend. I didn&apos;t think it would be possible, but I loved it more.<br/>******************************************************************************<br/>The Scorpio Races is easily the best book I&apos;ve read all year (out of about 50 so far, give or take). As a lover of all things mythical (vampires, werewolves, faeries; Oh, my!)in addition to being a HUGE Maggie Stiefvater fan, I have been giddy with excitement about the release of this novel. My expectations were high. In typical &quot;Ma</span>
  <span id="freeText627315700022133384" style="display:none">Re-Read this over the weekend. I didn't think it would be possible, but I loved it more.<br />******************************************************************************<br />The Scorpio Races is easily the best book I've read all year (out of about 50 so far, give or take). As a lover of all things mythical (vampires, werewolves, faeries; Oh, my!)in addition to being a HUGE Maggie Stiefvater fan, I have been giddy with excitement about the release of this novel. My expectations were high. In typical "Maggie" fashion, Ms. Steifvater far surpassed them with her intricately spun tale of the water horses of Thisby and the people that have a love-hate relationship with the wild beasts. This tale, told by any other, would seem too far-fetched to even pique interest, but because it is Maggie's.....and it is so very, very Maggie; it totally rocks, and must be reviewed Stiefvater-style.<br /><br />Top Reasons to Read The Scorpio Races--a novel that "amuses and delights me".<br />1. All things Maggie: compelling, colorful characters; awe-inspiring animals, kissing, readers crying and, well......someone will die. <br />2. The capaill uisce--the water horses. These amazing creatures have all of the characteristics of the horse that all 14-year-old girls dream of, only with deeply imbedded desires to kill or maim, and just a touch of faerie. Common sense says that we should fear them, but fantasy and hope force our hand, we fall in love with Sean Kendrick's Corr.<br />3. The bond between the Connolly siblings, particularly Finn and Puck, is endearing. The strength they derive from eachother, the support they lend and the constant spatting make for a realistic, yet enviable family. <br />4. Puck. She is strong, stubborn, spirited, proud, tenacious, angry, impatient, out-spoken and sharp-tongued. Also, she is sweet, kind, generous, supportive, understanding and full of love.<br />5. Sean. Slight but strong. A man of few words......for people that is, but plenty of sweet-things to whisper in the ears of the water horses.<br />6. The remaining characters. A couple, or three, eccentric, wise and wilely ladies. Very bad bad-guys. The despicable Mutt, his deplorable father and the interesting American. Each colorful and intriguing in his own right, yet all paling to the dynamic personalities of Sean and Puck.<br />7. Maggie Plus Moments. I have loved Ms. Stiefvater's writing style since I read Ballad, and it has been a pleasure to see it develop and refine throughout Lament and the Shiver Trilogy, but I was not prepared for the apparent exponential growth that I discovered in The Scorpio Races. Methinks Ms. Stiefvater has been into some Blood Magic. For example, in one tiny part of the book, her description of the races on the "mainland" is exquisite. The reader easily pictures the colors, the style of clothes, the atmosphere, even the weather; but the really crazy part is: the reader KNOWS that race is actually boring, and despite the detailed depiction, we'd choose the thrill of the pounding hooves by the deadly sea in the bitter cold any day.<br />Her sprinkled use of Irish phrasing and lilt remind the reader of the setting without repetitive statements. <br />8. Corr--Sean Kendrick's water horse and Dove--Puck's "island pony". The mutual adoration between animal and human is equisitely displayed time and again throughout the story. The story begins and ends with evidence of Sean Kendrick's love for his Corr, what makes a better story than that?</span>
  <a data-text-id="627315700022133384" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


